<h2>4) Decision tree</h2>
<ul>
  <li>If your team is under 5 agents and mostly email-based, prioritize ease-of-use and clean shared inbox workflows.</li>
  <li>If live chat is business-critical, prioritize real-time routing, assignment rules, and macro speed.</li>
  <li>If you support multiple products, prioritize tags, custom fields, and reporting filters from day one.</li>
  <li>If you need compliance and audit trails, prioritize stronger permissioning and history controls.</li>
  <li>If self-service is a priority, choose a stack with native knowledge base and deflection reporting.</li>
  <li>If you expect fast growth, choose tools that support team segmentation and advanced automation pathways.</li>
</ul>

<h2>5) Top picks breakdown</h2>
<h3>Pick A: Help Scout (Best overall for small teams)</h3>
<p><strong>Best for:</strong> Teams that want a calm UI, fast onboarding, and straightforward support operations.</p>
<p><strong>Avoid if:</strong> You require enterprise-level omnichannel complexity immediately.</p>
<p><strong>Pros:</strong></p>
<ul><li>Simple team adoption for new support reps.</li><li>Strong shared inbox model for smaller organizations.</li><li>Works well with lightweight process documentation.</li></ul>
<p><strong>Cons:</strong></p>
<ul><li>Some advanced routing use cases may require external tooling.</li><li>Deep analytics may require additional reporting workflows.</li><li>Complex multi-brand segmentation is less central than in larger suites.</li></ul>
<p><strong>Setup notes:</strong></p>
<ul><li>Define mailbox ownership and escalation rules early.</li><li>Build a base macro library around top ticket categories.</li><li>Run weekly QA review on first-reply quality and handle time.</li></ul>
<p><strong>Alternatives:</strong> Freshdesk, Zendesk Suite.</p>

<h3>Pick B: Freshdesk starter stack (Best lean team)</h3>
<p><strong>Best for:</strong> Small teams that need broad capabilities quickly with manageable setup effort.</p>
<p><strong>Avoid if:</strong> Your organization needs a messenger-first support strategy.</p>
<p><strong>Pros:</strong></p>
<ul><li>Broad baseline feature set for ticketing and channel support.</li><li>Good template and scenario support for repeatable responses.</li><li>Practical progression path as ticket volume grows.</li></ul>
<p><strong>Cons:</strong></p>
<ul><li>UI and workflow complexity can increase as rules accumulate.</li><li>Reporting consistency requires disciplined tagging.</li><li>Some teams may over-configure too early.</li></ul>
<p><strong>Setup notes:</strong></p>
<ul><li>Start with limited automation and expand gradually.</li><li>Use 8-12 core tags only during initial rollout.</li><li>Review reassignment volume weekly to tune routing.</li></ul>
<p><strong>Alternatives:</strong> Help Scout, Gorgias.</p>

<h3>Pick C: Intercom or Zendesk (Best scaling)</h3>
<p><strong>Best for:</strong> Teams expecting higher chat volume, more channels, and deeper automation.</p>
<p><strong>Avoid if:</strong> Your team has no admin owner for system governance.</p>
<p><strong>Pros:</strong></p>
<ul><li>Supports richer automation and routing structures.</li><li>Better for segmented teams and advanced workflows.</li><li>Strong ecosystem for integrations and extensibility.</li></ul>
<p><strong>Cons:</strong></p>
<ul><li>Longer onboarding and configuration cycles.</li><li>Can be overpowered for very small teams.</li><li>Requires operational ownership to maintain quality.</li></ul>
<p><strong>Setup notes:</strong></p>
<ul><li>Model conversation taxonomy before importing legacy data.</li><li>Define bot escalation paths with agent override rules.</li><li>Launch with one KPI dashboard used by all managers.</li></ul>
<p><strong>Alternatives:</strong> Freshdesk advanced setup, Help Scout plus integrations.</p>

