<h2>8) Common mistakes (and how to avoid them)</h2>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Mistake:</strong> Too many tags at launch. <strong>Avoid:</strong> Start with a compact taxonomy.</li>
  <li><strong>Mistake:</strong> No macro governance. <strong>Avoid:</strong> Assign one owner for macro quality review.</li>
  <li><strong>Mistake:</strong> Chat has no escalation path. <strong>Avoid:</strong> Define clear handoff rules to ticket or specialist queue.</li>
  <li><strong>Mistake:</strong> SLA targets are copied from another company. <strong>Avoid:</strong> Set realistic SLAs from your staffing model.</li>
  <li><strong>Mistake:</strong> Reporting ignores quality metrics. <strong>Avoid:</strong> Track reopen rate, CSAT, and first-contact resolution.</li>
  <li><strong>Mistake:</strong> Documentation is stale. <strong>Avoid:</strong> Review top 10 articles monthly.</li>
</ul>

<h2>9) FAQ</h2>
<h3>What is the fastest way to launch a small-team support stack?</h3>
<p>Use a shared inbox-first platform, configure core macros, and start with a limited set of automations.</p>
<h3>Do we need live chat from day one?</h3>
<p>Not always. If volume is low, email-first with clear SLA commitments can be enough initially.</p>
<h3>How many automations should we create initially?</h3>
<p>Keep it small. Start with routing, SLA reminders, and one escalation automation.</p>
<h3>Should small teams prioritize AI features?</h3>
<p>Only after base workflows are stable. AI works best when taxonomy, macros, and QA are already strong.</p>
<h3>How often should macros be reviewed?</h3>
<p>Monthly at minimum, and sooner if product changes affect support answers.</p>
<h3>What is a good migration strategy from inbox-only support?</h3>
<p>Import recent context, keep labels simple, and run dual operation briefly before full cutover.</p>

<p><strong>Implementation reality check:</strong> no tool choice can compensate for unclear ownership boundaries. Before vendor evaluation, document who owns triage, who owns escalations, and who approves macro changes. Teams that define those basics first usually launch faster and avoid the common second-month rework cycle where automation rules conflict with real-world staffing patterns.</p>

